Since the period is four years and the interest rate is compounded per quarter, we will use 16 as the period, representing how many quarters there are in four years.

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Period} &= \text{4 years}\times\text{4 quarters in a year}
\\[5pt]
&= {16}
\end{aligned}$$

Hence, we will consider 16 as the period we will use in our calculation.

Let's now determine the value should our bank accounts have today to achieve the goal.

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Present Value of an Annuity} &=\$2,500\times\dfrac{1-\dfrac{1}{\left(1+0.0057\right)^{16}}}{0.0057}
\\[10pt]
&=\$2,500\times\dfrac{1-\dfrac{1}{\left(1.0057\right)^{16}}}{0.0057}
\\[10pt]
&= \boxed{\bf\$38,126.53}
\end{aligned}$$


**Therefore, based on our calculation, we will need to have $38,126.53 in our bank account if, after three months, we want to withdraw $2,500 for the next four years with an interest rate of 0.57%.**
